        <h3>Case study: Tower Hamlets ‘Whole Systems’ breast-cancer screening programme</h3>
		<p>Authority type: <b>London Borough</b><br>
			Political affiliation: <b>Labour</b></p>
		<p><strong>The London Borough of Tower Hamlets has historically low participation rates in breast screening. To improve uptake, and therefore breast cancer mortality, the primary care trust designed a ‘whole systems’ approach tackling the problem from a number of different directions. The result was a 20 per cent improvement from 2005 to 2008. </strong></p> 
		<p>Tower Hamlets is a deprived borough in London’s East End with a large minority ethnic population (mostly Bangladeshi) and considerable levels of deprivation, both of which contribute reduced screening uptake. After research, the public health team at NHS Tower Hamlets and Forster for Change, developed a campaign targeting the white and Bangladeshi populations in different ways.</p>
		<p>A pilot with influential community group Social Action for Health involved calling Bangladeshi women who did not attend their appointments, rebooking their appointments for them and, in some cases, providing transport for groups of women to attend, resulting in an uptake of 69 per cent.</p>
		<p>For White women, a local ambassador was appointed to spread positive messages about breast screening for health, and a ‘Bosom Buddy’ pilot launched asking women who had been screened to encourage a friend or family member to attend, and help them through the appointment. Women with low literacy or with English as a second language were sent ‘talking invitations’ while two GP practices proactively called women before they received their invitations, encouraging them to attend.</p>
		<p>In primary care, GPs were incentivised to screen additional eligible women and training was provided to all 20 practices that formed the 2007/2008 screening round. A Bangladeshi GP screening lead was appointed for the PCT and GPs set up alerts to provide reminders when women attended clinics for other reasons. 10 per cent of women were also sent text messages, with an uptake rate of 70 per cent.</p>
		<p>Finally, the trust employed an external company to address the efficiency of call handling, leading to the set up of a dedicated call centre for the screening program, a 38 per cent drop in missed calls within a two-week period and a greater chance of women attending their appointments.</p>
